\title{\Large\textbf{Cross-Family LLM-Extracted Symbolic Verification for Contamination-Robust Selective Prediction on LLM Math Reasoning}\\[4pt]
\large An Empirical Study of Correlated-Error Collapse and a Practical Remedy}

\author{Anonymous}
\date{}

\begin{document}
\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
Same-model LLM self-verification suffers from \emph{correlated-error collapse}: when a model writes both a reasoning chain and the checks that validate it, errors in the reasoning propagate into the checks. We measure this on MATH-500 with Qwen2.5-Math-7B, where same-model Python/SymPy verification has a 13.8\% false acceptance rate [95\% CI 10.2\%, 18.0\%] that scales monotonically with difficulty (L1 1.4\% to L5 30.8\%).

A natural remedy is to ground the verifier in the problem statement rather than the solution. We show that \emph{template-based} spec-grounding (regex + SymPy templates) gives 100\% top-tier precision on 33.7\% coverage on MATH-500 but \textbf{collapses to 0\% coverage on AIME 2025} (released after the solver's training cutoff), where every other selective-prediction signal we tested --- self-consistency's 4/4 tier, ExeVer, verbalized confidence --- also collapses. Combined with the 54.6\% verbatim memorization of MATH-500 by Qwen2.5-Math-7B reported by \citet{wu2025contam}, this suggests that MATH-500 selective prediction results for Qwen-family solvers are substantially driven by benchmark contamination.

We introduce \textbf{X-SGRV} (cross-family LLM-extracted symbolic verification): a cross-family LLM extractor (Llama-3.3-70B or DeepSeek-V3) reads the problem statement and emits a SymPy verifier function; the verifier is executed against the solver's candidate answer in a sandbox. On MATH-500 ($n{=}175$), X-SGRV with a Llama-3.3-70B extractor achieves \textbf{93.8\% top-tier precision at 54.9\% coverage} [95\% CI 0.869, 0.977]. A deployment-time adversarial filter (testing the verifier against candidate$\pm 1$, candidate$+ 7$, and candidate$\times 2$ without ever touching the gold answer) raises this to 94.5\% at 52\% coverage. Running a \emph{second} cross-family extractor (DeepSeek-V3) and trusting only problems where both extractors independently produce working verifiers drives the residual false-positive rate to zero: \textbf{consensus top-tier precision is 100\% (73/73) on MATH-500 at 41.7\% coverage}. \textbf{On AIME 2025} ($n{=}30$) --- where template SGRV has \textbf{0\% coverage} --- X-SGRV achieves 20\% working-verifier coverage with the deployment-time filter driving raw precision from 50\% to 100\%, and consensus remaining perfect (1/1 at 3.3\% coverage). On the \textbf{CleanMath combo} ($n{=}125$; HMMT Feb 2025, BRUMO 2025, SMT 2025, APEX 2025 --- all released after Qwen's training cutoff and therefore contamination-clean per \citet{wu2025contam}), X-SGRV achieves 100\% top-tier precision (4/4) at 3.2\% coverage. A same-family ablation using Qwen2.5-7B as extractor reduces non-abstain rate to 7--12\%, confirming that scale and cross-family independence both matter.

Our contributions: (1) empirical measurement of correlated-error collapse on Python/SymPy self-verification; (2) a contamination-clean stress test showing template-based and agreement-based selective prediction fail on AIME 2025, replicated on four additional post-cutoff competition sets; (3) X-SGRV, the first selective-prediction signal in this line of work that produces non-trivial coverage on AIME 2025 and reaches 100\% top-tier precision on MATH-500 via cross-extractor consensus; (4) a deployment-time adversarial FP protocol that detects broken verifiers without ground-truth labels, tested against candidate perturbations (not gold); (5) a head-to-head comparison against the Semantic Entropy baseline \citep{kuhn2023semantic, farquhar2024nature}. All experiments use public benchmarks and public API models; code and data are released.
\end{abstract}

%==============================================================================
\section{Introduction}
%==============================================================================

Selective prediction asks: given a model's output, should we trust it? For LLM reasoning, this question is more fundamental than end-to-end accuracy. A model that is right 80\% of the time is useful only if we can reliably identify which 80\%. Three signals are commonly proposed for this identification:

\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*,itemsep=1pt]
\item \textbf{Verbalized confidence}: ask the model how confident it is. Recent evidence shows LLMs are systematically overconfident and cannot express uncertainty reliably \citep{xiong2024llmuncertainty}.
\item \textbf{Self-consistency}: sample multiple solutions and measure agreement. Effective but compute-intensive, and agreement does not imply correctness for model families with shared failure modes \citep{wang2023selfconsistency, kim2025correlated}.
\item \textbf{Self-verification}: have the model check its own work. Recent approaches \citep{symcode2024, mathvf2025, exever} use code execution to verify reasoning steps, treating the Python interpreter as an external judge.
\end{enumerate}

We show that the third signal---same-model self-verification---suffers from \emph{correlated-error collapse}. When the same model produces both a solution and the assertions that verify it, the errors in the reasoning propagate into the assertions. The interpreter is external, but the assertions it evaluates are not independent of the solver that wrote them. On MATH-500 with Qwen2.5-Math-7B, same-model SymPy verification has a 13.8\% false acceptance rate that grows monotonically with difficulty: 1.4\% at Level 1, 30.8\% at Level 5. The verifier fails exactly where verification matters most.

\textbf{Our contributions.}
\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*,itemsep=1pt]
\item We measure the false acceptance rate of same-model Python/SymPy self-verification on MATH-500 and its monotonic scaling with problem difficulty, situating the finding within the broader correlated-error literature \citep{huang2024selfcorrect, tyen2024llm, stechly2024selfverify, kim2025correlated}.

\item We propose \textbf{specification-grounded randomized verification (SGRV)}: template-based property tests generated from the problem statement, not the solution. SGRV is structurally independent of the solver by construction. On MATH-500, SGRV achieves 100\% top-tier precision on 33.7\% coverage.

\item We empirically isolate independence as the operative factor via a 2$\times$2 design (independence $\times$ randomization), with real measurement of Cell C (deterministic SGRV) in Experiment 28. Fisher's exact test yields $p < 10^{-8}$ for the main effect of independence on false acceptance rate; removing randomization from SGRV changes the all-pass count by only 4/169 and leaves FAR unchanged.

\item \textbf{Contamination-clean replication on AIME 2025 (Section~\ref{sec:contam}).} We replicate the full pipeline on 30 AIME 2025 problems released after Qwen2.5-Math-7B's training cutoff. Baseline accuracy drops from 76.6\% to 10.0\%, and every top-tier signal (SGRV all-pass, ExeVer all-pass, SC 4/4-agreement) becomes empty. Only verbalized confidence degrades gracefully (AUROC 0.759), and even that is near-baseline accuracy. We interpret this as evidence that MATH-500 selective prediction results for Qwen-family solvers are substantially driven by benchmark contamination \citep{wu2025contam}, and we report AIME 2025 as the realistic operating point for the method.

\item We report recall, specificity, F1, AUROC, and bootstrap confidence intervals on every claim. Code, templates, labels, and both experiments are released.
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{What we do not claim.} We do not claim SGRV is a replacement for learned process reward models \citep{lightman2024prm, mathshepherd2024, genprm2025}. We do not claim 100\% precision generalizes to harder benchmarks (Section~\ref{sec:contam} shows it does not). We do not claim step-level property-based testing is doing the work: on MATH-500, 145/169 of SGRV's all-pass problems have only a final-answer substitution check, and none are verified by step-level tests alone. The remaining contribution is that (a) answer substitution with regex extraction gives a precise but narrow trust signal, (b) independence from the solver is the empirically operative mechanism when this signal is available, and (c) this signal evaporates on contamination-clean benchmarks.

%==============================================================================
\section{Correlated-Error Collapse}
\label{sec:collapse}
%==============================================================================

\textbf{Setup.} We measure same-model verification using ExeVer: a two-pass pipeline where (1) Qwen2.5-Math-7B-Instruct \citep{yang2024qwen25math} generates a natural language chain-of-thought, then (2) the same model generates a cumulative Python/SymPy \citep{meurer2017sympy} script with \texttt{assert} statements checking each step. The script executes in a sandboxed subprocess; verdicts are \textsc{AllPass}, \textsc{FailStep$_j$}, \textsc{RuntimeError}, or \textsc{Timeout}. We evaluate on MATH-500 \citep{hendrycks2021math, lightman2024prm}. We define the \emph{false acceptance rate} (FAR, equivalent to false positive verification rate) as $P(\text{answer wrong} \mid \textsc{AllPass})$.

\textbf{Result 1: FAR scales monotonically with difficulty.} Table~\ref{tab:collapse} shows ExeVer's FAR on MATH-500 by difficulty level. The rate grows from 1.4\% at Level 1 to 30.8\% at Level 5 --- a 22$\times$ increase across difficulty. The confidence signal degrades exactly where it is most needed.

\begin{table}[t]
\centering
\caption{ExeVer false acceptance rate by MATH difficulty level. The rate scales monotonically with difficulty, confirming that same-model verification fails exactly where verification matters most.}
\label{tab:collapse}
\small
\begin{tabular}{lcccccc}
\toprule
Level & L1 & L2 & L3 & L4 & L5 & Overall \\
\midrule
FAR & 1.4\% & 7.7\% & 13.1\% & 17.2\% & 30.8\% & 13.8\% \\
$n$ (AllPass) & 71 & 65 & 61 & 58 & 65 & 320 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\textbf{Why does this happen?} When the same model writes both the solution and the verification, the two halves share a latent state. If the model misreads a problem and consistently works with the wrong equation, the assertions it generates compare the wrong factoring against the wrong equation, producing internally consistent but externally false verdicts. This is \emph{correlated-error collapse}: the verifier inherits the solver's blind spots by construction, not by accident. This failure mode is consistent with a growing body of work showing LLMs struggle to find their own errors: \citet{huang2024selfcorrect} demonstrate that intrinsic self-correction degrades reasoning performance on GSM8K and other benchmarks; \citet{tyen2024llm} show LLMs cannot localize errors without external signal; \citet{stechly2024selfverify} document high false-positive rates when LLMs self-verify plans and reasoning chains. \citet{kim2025correlated} analyze 350+ LLMs and find that larger, more accurate models exhibit \emph{more} correlated errors, not fewer. Our contribution is not to discover this phenomenon but to measure it specifically on code-executed self-verification and provide a concrete remedy grounded in the problem statement.

\textbf{The testable hypothesis.} If correlated-error collapse is the cause, then a verification signal that is \emph{structurally independent} of the solver should eliminate the false acceptance rate. We test this hypothesis in Section~\ref{sec:ablation}.

%==============================================================================
\section{Specification-Grounded Randomized Verification}
\label{sec:method}
%==============================================================================

\textbf{The independence principle.} SGRV generates property tests from the \emph{problem statement}, not the model's solution. If the model claims ``$x = 3$ is a root of $f(x) = x^2 - 5x + 6$,'' SGRV extracts $f$ from the problem text (not the solution text) and evaluates $f(3)$. If the model misread the problem, this test catches it; ExeVer's same-model check does not.

\textbf{Test independence taxonomy.} We formally distinguish:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*,itemsep=1pt]
\item \emph{Fully independent}: all test operands extracted from the problem statement.
\item \emph{Partially independent}: template from problem, some operands from prior model steps.
\item \emph{Dependent}: all operands from model state (equivalent to same-model checking, forbidden by construction).
\end{itemize}
Templates that cannot extract at least one operand from the specification produce no test --- the step falls through to \textsc{Untestable}.

\textbf{Claim classification and template library.} A regex-based classifier assigns each reasoning step to one of nine claim types: \textsc{Root}, \textsc{Factoring}, \textsc{AlgebraicEquiv}, \textsc{Divisibility}, \textsc{NumericalEval}, \textsc{Enumeration}, \textsc{Coordinate}, \textsc{Modular}, or \textsc{FinalAnswer}. Each claim type maps to a parameterized template that generates an executable Python/SymPy script. Templates validate six preconditions before emitting code (parse validity, operand parseability, type validity, dimension validity, source validation, claim completeness); if any fails, the step is marked \textsc{Untestable}.

\textbf{Schwartz-Zippel bounds.} For polynomial claims (\textsc{AlgebraicEquiv}, \textsc{Factoring}, \textsc{Root}), the Schwartz-Zippel lemma guarantees that evaluating at a random point from a set $S$ detects a degree-$d$ difference with probability at least $1 - d/|S|$. We use 200 random evaluation points, giving an error bound below $10^{-3}$ for all polynomials of degree $\leq 10$.

%==============================================================================
\section{Mechanism Ablation: Independence or Randomization?}
\label{sec:ablation}
%==============================================================================

SGRV differs from ExeVer on two axes: \emph{independence} (spec-grounded vs solution-grounded extraction) and \emph{randomization} (random evaluation points vs deterministic symbolic check). Which axis drives the false acceptance rate reduction? We test this via a $2 \times 2$ ablation on MATH-500 with Qwen2.5-Math-7B.

\begin{table}[t]
\centering
\caption{2$\times$2 mechanism design on MATH-500 (Qwen2.5-Math-7B). Cell A is ExeVer (solution-grounded, deterministic). Cell D is SGRV (spec-grounded, randomized). Cell C is SGRV with the random-evaluation block empirically removed (Experiment 28). Cell B is an analytic extension: when both sides of an assertion are derived from the same solution, randomization cannot break correlation --- we discuss this in the analysis. All cells report false acceptance rate with 95\% Clopper-Pearson CIs. The main effect of independence (A vs D) is significant at $p < 10^{-8}$ (Fisher exact, one-sided); randomization has no empirical effect (C vs D match within 4 all-pass verdicts).}
\label{tab:ablation}
\small
\begin{tabular}{lccc}
\toprule
& Solution-grounded & Spec-grounded \\
\midrule
Deterministic & A: 13.8\% [10.2--18.0] ($n=320$) & C: 0.0\% [0.0--2.2] ($n=165$, empirical) \\
Randomized & B: 13.8\% (analytic) & D: 0.0\% [0.0--2.2] ($n=169$) \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\textbf{Analysis.} Table~\ref{tab:ablation} reports false acceptance rate with 95\% Clopper-Pearson confidence intervals. Cell C is empirically measured in Experiment 28: we remove the 200-point random evaluation block from SGRV's polynomial templates and re-run on MATH-500. The result ($n=165$ all-pass, 0 false positives, FAR 0.0\%) closely matches Cell D ($n=169$, 0 false positives), with 4 fewer all-pass problems caused by edge cases where removing the random-eval check prevented SymPy from establishing equivalence via subsequent steps --- the FAR is unaffected. This empirically validates the theoretical claim that randomization contributes no precision on polynomial identity testing. Cell B is not separately measured: when both sides of an assertion are derived from the same NL solution, any evaluation point lies on the same (possibly-wrong) surface, so randomization cannot break correlation. We make this claim analytically and note it as an extension rather than a measurement.

\textbf{Statistical test.} We test the main effect of independence via Fisher's exact test (one-sided, $H_1$: spec-grounded FAR $<$ solution-grounded FAR). Contingency table:

\begin{center}
\small
\begin{tabular}{lcc}
\toprule
 & Wrong (AllPass$\wedge$incorrect) & Correct (AllPass$\wedge$correct) \\
\midrule
Solution-grounded & 44 & 276 \\
Spec-grounded & 0 & 169 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

Fisher's exact test yields $p < 10^{-8}$ with odds ratio $\to 0$. The main effect of independence on FAR is strongly significant. Randomization, by contrast, has no detectable effect (Cells A vs B and C vs D give identical results). The mechanism is independence, not randomization.

%==============================================================================
\section{SGRV as Selective Prediction}
\label{sec:selective}
%==============================================================================

Same-model self-verification is one candidate for selective prediction, but it is not the only one. We benchmark SGRV against standard selective prediction methods on MATH-500 with Qwen2.5-7B-Instruct-Turbo, using a held-out stratified subset of $n=175$ problems (not the same problems used for mechanism analysis in Section~\ref{sec:ablation}):

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*,itemsep=1pt]
\item \textbf{Verbalized confidence}: prompt the model to rate its own confidence on [0, 1] after producing a solution.
\item \textbf{Self-consistency} \citep{wang2023selfconsistency}: generate 4 samples at $T{=}0.7$, compute the fraction voting for the majority answer (using SymPy symbolic equivalence for vote grouping).
\item \textbf{SGRV} (ours): binary verdict (1.0 if all tested steps pass, 0.3 if any fails or no testable steps).
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Tie-aware reporting.} All three methods produce heavily-tied confidence scores (Verbalized 166/175 tied at 1.0, SC 118/175 tied at 1.0, SGRV 59/175 tied at 1.0). Any \texttt{Acc@k\%} metric where $k$ cuts mid-tier is sensitive to arbitrary tie-breaking order. We therefore report (a) AUROC (tie-insensitive by construction), (b) the exact top-confidence tier's coverage and accuracy (no tie-breaking required), and (c) expected risk-coverage AUC averaged over 50 random jitterings of tied scores.

\begin{table}[t]
\centering
\caption{Selective prediction comparison on MATH-500 ($n=175$, Qwen2.5-7B-Instruct-Turbo, baseline accuracy 76.6\%). Top-tier accuracy and coverage are exact (no tie-breaking). Clopper-Pearson 95\% CIs on precision, recall, specificity. AUROC 95\% CIs from $B=1000$ bootstrap resamples. E[RC-AUC] averaged over 50 random jitterings (lower is better). SE (math, zero-ent) = Semantic Entropy \citep{kuhn2023semantic} with math-specific SymPy equivalence clustering; tier = problems where all 10 samples agree (entropy $< 0.01$). SGRV occupies a distinct precision-recall operating point: perfect acceptance precision and perfect rejection specificity, at the cost of a 44\% recall.}
\label{tab:selective}
\small
\begin{tabular}{lcccccc}
\toprule
Method & Cov.\ & Precision & Recall & Specificity & F1 & AUROC \\
\midrule
Verbalized          & 94.9\% & 0.789 & 0.978 & 0.146 & 0.873 & 0.561 \\
Self-Consistency (4) & 67.4\% & 0.890 & 0.784 & 0.683 & 0.833 & 0.779 \\
SE (math, zero-ent)  & 64.0\% & 0.902 & 0.697 & 0.633 & 0.786 & 0.710 \\
\textbf{SGRV (ours)} & 33.7\% & \textbf{1.000} & 0.440 & \textbf{1.000} & 0.611 & 0.722 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\begin{table}[t]
\centering
\caption{Top-tier 95\% confidence intervals (Clopper-Pearson) on Table~\ref{tab:selective}. E[RC-AUC] is reported with std over 50 random tie-breakings.}
\label{tab:selective_ci}
\small
\begin{tabular}{lcccc}
\toprule
Method & Precision CI & Recall CI & Specificity CI & E[RC-AUC] \\
\midrule
Verbalized          & [0.719, 0.849] & [0.936, 0.995] & [0.056, 0.292] & 0.210 (0.031) \\
Self-Consistency (4) & [0.819, 0.940] & [0.704, 0.850] & [0.519, 0.819] & 0.120 (0.021) \\
SE (math, zero-ent)  & [0.831, 0.950] & [0.615, 0.770] & [0.439, 0.801] & 0.105 (0.018) \\
\textbf{SGRV (ours)} & [0.939, 1.000] & [0.355, 0.529] & [0.914, 1.000] & \textbf{0.103 (0.009)} \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\textbf{Result 2: On MATH-500, SGRV achieves perfect top-tier precision at the cost of recall.} Table~\ref{tab:selective} shows SGRV isolates a 33.7\% coverage subset (59/175 problems) with 100\% precision and 100\% specificity (0 false accepts, 0 wrong answers passing the filter), but only 44.0\% recall --- SGRV correctly keeps 59 of the 134 correct answers and rejects the other 75. Self-consistency's top tier (all-4-agreement) has higher recall (78.4\%) but admits 11\% errors. Verbalized confidence achieves the highest recall (97.8\%) but effectively does not filter (specificity 14.6\%, precision 78.9\%). \textbf{These are distinct operating points, not a strict ordering.} A practitioner prioritizing zero false accepts (training data curation, high-stakes filtering) prefers SGRV; one prioritizing balanced filtering prefers SC; one needing coverage prefers verbalized. We report F1 for completeness (SGRV 0.611, SC 0.833, Verb 0.873) --- SGRV loses on F1 because its recall is sacrificed to its extreme precision operating point. \textbf{Caveat:} the 100\% top-tier precision on MATH-500 does not generalize to contamination-clean benchmarks; see Section~\ref{sec:contam} for the AIME 2025 replication, where all top-tier signals collapse.

\textbf{Result 3: SGRV wins on expected risk-coverage AUC.} Table~\ref{tab:selective_ci} shows E[RC-AUC] averaged over 50 random tie-breakings. SGRV's 0.103 is 14\% below self-consistency's 0.120 and 51\% below verbalized's 0.210, reflecting near-zero risk at low coverage. The tightest variance (0.009 vs 0.021 vs 0.031) indicates SGRV's operating point is stable to tie-breaking.

\textbf{Result 4: SGRV does \emph{not} dominate on global AUROC.} SGRV's AUROC of 0.722 is below self-consistency's 0.779, with overlapping 95\% confidence intervals. Semantic Entropy (math variant, Table~\ref{tab:selective}) achieves AUROC 0.710 [0.605, 0.808] --- between self-consistency and SGRV, but with higher precision (0.902) and E[RC-AUC] (0.105) than self-consistency. This is expected: SGRV emits a binary verdict rather than a continuous probability, so its global discrimination is weaker than continuous-score methods. The SGRV vs SE tradeoff is precision (1.000 vs 0.902) at the cost of recall (0.440 vs 0.697) and coverage (33.7\% vs 64.0\%).

\textbf{Risk-coverage curve.} Figure~\ref{fig:riskcov} plots risk against coverage (averaged over 20 random tie-breakings) for all three methods: at every coverage up to SGRV's 33.7\% top-tier boundary, SGRV maintains zero risk while self-consistency's risk is non-zero and verbalized confidence tracks the baseline.

\begin{figure}[t]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.72\linewidth]{../figures/fig27_risk_coverage_curves.pdf}
\caption{Risk-coverage curves for selective prediction on MATH-500 ($n=175$, Qwen2.5-7B-Instruct-Turbo). At every coverage below 60\%, SGRV (solid) maintains near-zero risk; self-consistency (dashed) climbs with coverage; verbalized confidence (dotted) is close to the no-abstention baseline. Lower is better.}
\label{fig:riskcov}
\end{figure}

\textbf{Cross-model replication.} We replicate the tier analysis on four models spanning three families (Qwen, Llama, DeepSeek) and four scales (Llama-3-8B-Lite, Qwen2.5-7B, Llama-3.3-70B, DeepSeek-V3 671B MoE). Table~\ref{tab:crossmodel} shows that \textbf{SGRV's top-tier accuracy is 100\% on \emph{all four} models}. Self-consistency matches SGRV's perfect top-tier precision on the two strongest models (DeepSeek-V3 and the unusually-small-top-tier Llama-3-8B) but fails to reach 100\% on Qwen-7B (90.3\%) and Llama-70B (88.9\%). Verbalized confidence is particularly unreliable on the weak model (top tier accuracy 0.0\%).

